The inequality to be proved is effectively $\sup_{s \le t} \|X^{\tau}_s\| \le K + \mathbb{1}_{\{\tau \le t\}} \|X_\tau\|$.
Analyzing the cases:
1. If $s < \tau$, then by definition of hitting time (as an infimum), $\|X_s\| < K$. Thus $\|X^\tau_s\| = \|X_s\| < K$.
2. If $\tau \le s$, then $\|X^\tau_s\| = \|X_\tau\|$. Since $\tau \le s \le t$, the indicator is 1, and we need $\|X_\tau\| \le K + \|X_\tau\|$, which reduces to $0 \le K$.

The statement implies $K$ serves as a bound, but strictly speaking, the inequality holds for the case $\tau \le s$ only if $0 \le K$. Furthermore, if $s < \tau$ exists, $\|X_s\| < K$ with $\|X_s\| \ge 0$ implies $K > 0$. If $K < 0$, the hitting time would be $\bot$ (assuming $\bot$ is in the domain and $X$ starts somewhere), leading to $0 \le K$ being required. Thus, the lemma requires the assumption $0 \le K$. I will add `(hK : 0 ≤ K)` to the lemma arguments to make it provable and provide the proof.

